i think about this day everyday, and dread it as it comes closer. i try avoid everything that this day has done but at the end of the day i live with it and wear it like an article of clothing. it's been 5 years and i still live with the effects of its wrath, but today i found some strength to look this demon in the face; though, i couldn't manage to leave my car i still came. to some it would look like a park but to me it's a place that my life turned upside down. someday i will look at it as just a park or just a place that holds memory but this is the first step toward that. i owe it to 17 year old me to be strong, happy, healthy, and worthy of love. 
#metoo #endthestigma #surviving

text:
#rkelly #justice #helpwomen r. kelly was charged with multiple counts of criminal sexual abuse in a chicago court friday after decades of rumors and allegations that the r&b star was abusing women and underage girls.

tandra simonton, spokeswoman for the cook county state's attorney's office, confirmed to the associated press the charges had been filed against the 52-year-old grammy winner but declined to say the specific number. media reports said there were 10 counts, at least some involving an underage victim or victims.

michael avenatti: r. kelly seen having sex with underage girl in newly uncovered video

kelly has denied allegations of sexual misconduct involving women and underage girls for decades. neither kellyâ€™s legal representative nor the cook county prosecutor's office immediately responded to fox newsâ€™ request for comment on the charges.

the singer, whose full name is robert kelly, is one of the top-selling recording artists of all time. he has won multiple grammys, including for his hit song, "i believe i can fly." his arrest sets the stage for another #metoo-era celebrity trial after bill cosby went to prison last year, and former hollywood studio boss harvey weinstein is awaiting trial.

text:
israelâ€™s not your toy â€œlife is big, but i like my jewelry even bigger!â€ is a perfect introductory quote from liat ginzberg, israel's trendiest and bold jewelry designer. we first connected years ago at bijoux at the norton museum of art. the yearly event hosts several top israeli jewelry designers and is chaired by none other than my second mom, donna schneier. since i am a big jewelry fan in every sense of the word big, i immediately gravitated towards liat's collection. over the years we have formed a great friendship and she has customized an assortment of pieces for me that are bold, big, beautiful and brazen. perfectly suited for the occasions as new york fashion week or tv appearances in which my accessories need to say a lot! 
liat has grown over the years to include a multitude of vogue editorials, but her current most famous admirer is the israeli singing sensation netta . the marriage of liat and netta is perfect. they are both an outrageous example of self love and patriotism. neither one shrinks to accommodate anyone who thinks otherwise. of course i'll explain my statement. 
liat ginzberg's jewelry are daring, one of a kind pieces with their abundant use of color and electrifying style. the designs express a nostalgic yet current view on the 90`s club scene combined with hints of frida khalo, carmen meranda, lucille ball and madonna. 
each piece is composed of vintage elements from the 70`s and the 80`s, which liat collects on her travels around the world. all these elements and influences produce a perfectly unique style that is all her own. liat never compromises to trends, she remains herself in each earring, bracelet and necklace. 
netta , born netta barzilai, winner of eurovision 2018, approached the music scene with a huge entrance. her song toy became an anthem for the #metoo movement as well as an international number 1 hit. â€œbarzilai's style might not be everyone's cup of tea, but her carnival-like appearance is an antithesis of the demand placed on israeli artists to shrink, appear nonchalant and not draw too much attention to themselves.â€ says ynet news. @nettabarzi @liatginzburg @ynetgram @queensjewishlink @queensjewishlink

text:
in 2 weeks im moving back to san diego.  when i first lived in socal, i was a 32 year old in the midst of battling for my mental health.  just a few months prior to my move, i began getting treatment for cptsd.  my nervous breakdown was the simplest scary moment iâ€™ve known and i moved to socal to escape my past life. .
.
i hated living there.  i felt alone.  i felt isolated. i felt terrified of what went on in my mind and body.  i took that out on san diego, and left as soon as i could. .
.
last summer i went back for a last minute visit and by the end of the weekend was overflowing with the amount of love that had been poured into me and the words that displayed how much i was cared for.  it was way more than i knew, i just couldnâ€™t see it. .
.
so, now i return.  i return to the walks along the tide, and the sunsets that hit the ocean so intently that you canâ€™t tell where the water ends and the sky begins.  i return to the many who saw i was hurting and felt restless on how to help me. i return as a very whole, strong, healthy man who is determined to make a difference in other people lives, because wrestling with mental health is a lonely path. .
.
so, today i say to you:  when was the last time you daydreamed about your hardest chapter being over? what do you need to hear today to know without a shadow of a doubt, that your pain has an ending place and the journey of resolution is around the corner? .
.
please accept this as a big virtual hug.... to you! you, the one struggling and feeling overwhelmed.  you, the one holding on because your honesty is not accepted in your environment.  you, because you need to know you are seen and known... you are!! and, you are loved too!!
.
.
keep fighting your battle....xoxo
.
.

.
so, today i say to you:  when was the last time you daydreamed about your hardest chapter being over? what do you need to hear today to know without a shadow of a doubt, that your pain has an ending place and the journey of resolution is around the corner? .
.
please accept this as a big viual hug.... to you! you, the one struggling and feeling overwhelmed.  you, the one holding on because your honesty is not accepted in your environment.  you, because you need to know you are seen and known... you are!! and, you are loved too!!
.
.
keep fighting your battle....xoxo
.
.

the r&b superstar has faced nearly two decades of accusations of sexual abuse. and last thursday, cook county prosecutors reportedly received a 45-minute videotape that is said to show kelly performing multiple sex acts with an underage girl, whom both kelly and the girl describe on tape as being 14 years old.

maybe not me too,
maybe my skirt was too short
and my shirt was too tight,
maybe i did drink too much,
and i didnâ€™t say no loud enough.
maybe i thought i was clear,
but maybe you didnâ€™t quite hear.
maybe my screams were whispers
and maybe the taste of my lips said kiss her,
maybe i didnâ€™t fight,
maybe my mind was on flight
maybe not me too,
but why am i nauseous just at the thought of you? 
why is this the accepted point of view?
why not me too?

text:
just finished reading the novel disclosure by michael crichton (one of my favorite authors), a story about a guy trying to prove he was being sexually harassed on the job by his female boss.
#
apparently, back in the early '90s, this book (as well as the movie) faced much criticism & controversy and i'm pretty sure, within today's #metoo movement, it might face criticism today. 
#
though not one of crichton's best (it starts off slow and at times gets bogged down in technical exposition), it's still a great read.
#andrereads #realmenread #disclosure #thrillernovel #michaelcrichton #90sfiction #corporatefiction #harrasment #predatorybehavior

text:
this workshop & support group is for women and men who need a safe space & support to heal from their experiences with sexual abuse. our main objective in this workshop series is to clear the psychological and energetic imprint that sexual trauma may have left on us that affects who we are and how we function in the world. it is so important and necessary that we reclaim our power over our sexuality and over our lives now and for generations to come, so that we may operate from a place of healing rather than a place of hurt. â€¢

within this safe space, you will have the option to share your experiences and insights openly, write them in your journal or simply listen and work through things internally. this is a judgment-free zone, and a space full of love and healing energy. the deep sense of relief from release, the empowerment from your courageousness, and the love from supportive peers can bring so much hope and healing that can change our lives in beautiful ways.
â€¢

in session 2, we will: âœ¨assess how we may re-create trauma in our lives
âœ¨identify ways to reclaim our safety
âœ¨identify how to listen to our bodies to better control our responses to triggers
âœ¨learn ways to process emotions
âœ¨establish a clear connection between the emotions and physical body responses
âœ¨learn new destressing techniques

text:
join @iamthecreatress in this workshop & support group for women and men who need a safe space & support to heal from their experiences with sexual abuse. our main objective in this workshop series is to clear the psychological and energetic imprint that sexual trauma may have left on us that affects who we are and how we function in the world. it is so important and necessary that we reclaim our power over our sexuality and over our lives now and for generations to come, so that we may operate from a place of healing rather than a place of hurt. â€¢

within this safe space, you will have the option to share your experiences and insights openly, write them in your journal or simply listen and work through things internally. this is a judgment-free zone, and a space full of love and healing energy. the deep sense of relief from release, the empowerment from your courageousness, and the love from supportive peers can bring so much hope and healing that can change our lives in beautiful ways.
â€¢

in session 2, we will: âœ¨assess how we may re-create trauma in our lives
âœ¨identify ways to reclaim our safety
âœ¨identify how to listen to our bodies to better control our responses to triggers
âœ¨learn ways to process emotions
âœ¨establish a clear connection between the emotions and physical body responses
âœ¨learn new destressing techniques

since our deepest traumas are imbedded in our guts and muscles, to free ourselves we must free our bodies. -

from infancy we are fed ideas of what strength is... "toughen up", "keep it together", "get over it". when we cut ourselves off from fully feeling it's like slamming on the gas and breaks at the same time.Â Â this is one example of how illness can manifest in our bodies. -

on the deepest level, change always involves the body. - - take a moment to ask where these uncomfortable feelings live in your body? - - acknowledge and thank them for their positive intentions. - - soften your body, breathe, and let yourself feel.

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
film review - â€œthe house that jack builtâ€ (2018) lars von trier (tap for sound)
â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”
tribute to bruno ganz (1941-2019)
â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”
the way i see it, there are two types of films about characters who commit various immoral acts; those which try to make us feel pity or forgive the character to a degree such as â€œamerican beautyâ€ or â€œlolitaâ€ and there are those which want us to be disgusted and hate the character. â€œthe house that jack builtâ€ is most definitely the latter. 
failed architect and vicious sociopath, jack retells his malicious acts in five randomly chosen acts which he calls â€˜incidentsâ€™. each incident is extremely visceral and leaves nothing to the imagination. in most films with heavy violence the violence is usually implied but not shown, von trier didnâ€™t do this though, no, the camera captures each horrific scene fully. 
out of the five incidents the most horrific and vile is the third incident in which jack murders a single mother and their two sons before using rigor mortis, sticks and wire to turn one of the boys into taxidermy. 
on the relatively lighter side of things, jackâ€™s second act is darkly comic as he fails to strangle a suspicious old woman before stabbing her. after hours of cleaning up, his ocd forces him to second guess himself and look over every nook and cranny multiple times. just when heâ€™s about to leave, a police officer arrives at the house. jack feeds the officer some lies and is on his merry way. to add to jackâ€™s hilarious comedy of errors, the ladyâ€™s body leaves a bloody trail all the way back to jackâ€™s storage freezer. as he realises this it begins to rain and wash away the trail. jack calls this a â€œmiracle from godâ€ much to his escort, virgilâ€™s dismay. 
well thatâ€™s just what is on the surface of the film, really the film is a big â€˜fuck youâ€™ from von trier to liberal complainers. he even casts uma thurman (a #metoo advocate) as a stupid, irritating woman who has it coming to her. i also think that von trier is trying to use the shock factor of â€˜the house that jack builtâ€™ as a way of expressing how liberal modern cinema is. 
an excellent film and definitely one of my favourites from 2018. 9.5/10.

- she [rebekah mercer] loved me. she was like, oh we need more of your type on our side!

your type? - the gays. she loved the gays. so did steve [bannon]. he saw us as early adopters. he figured, if you can get the gays on board, everyone else will follow. itâ€™s why he was so into the whole milo [yiannopoulos] thing.

robert mercer was a pioneer in ai and machine translation. he helped invent algorithmic trading â€“ which replaced hedge fund managers with computer programs â€“ and he listened to wylieâ€™s pitch. it was for a new kind of political message-targeting based on an influential and groundbreaking 2014 paper researched at cambridgeâ€™s psychometrics centre, called: - computer-based personality judgments are more accurate than those made by humans.
.
- in politics, the money man is usually the dumbest person in the room. whereas itâ€™s the opposite way around with mercer, says wylie. - he said very little, but he really listened. he wanted to understand the science. and he wanted proof that it worked.

text:
throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaignâ€™s use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of peopleâ€™s profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there â€œcould have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheatingâ€. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesdayâ€™s hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon
the guardian

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

text:
long post alert
_______

it would be factual to say that most days i don't feel "hot". actually i'm usually in sweat paints covered in food splatters from cooking or wax from crafts. this, however, was not one of those days. on this day, i was really feeling myself. i got several compliments that really tried to stroke my ego. 
_______

what you don't see is that just a week prior, i had one of the most stressful and pressing times of last year. i lost my best friend, and was in an uncomfortable situation with another close one. i was dealing with some heavy family things and it was just like things weren't aligning the way that i thought they would. 
________

the point is this, never look at the outer appearance and make assumptions about people. things in real life sometimes appear the way they do on social media: like everything is perfect, but it can be far from it. don't let people or social media blindly fool you into thinking that your life, career, purpose, or position are not where they should be and that their lifestyle is much greater. work hard in whatever it is that you do, be better than you were yesterday, and spread love to all that come on your path. 
_______

i'm thankful for those experiences, because they have brought me here: healthy, happy and whole. i've gained peace, wisdom, joy and understanding from those experiences, so when you see me, i still may have on those stain filled sweats, but know this... i'm good.

what was he like? - smart, says wylie. - interesting. really interested in ideas. heâ€™s the only straight man iâ€™ve ever talked to about intersectional feminist theory. he saw its relevance straightaway to the oppressions that conservative, young white men feel.

text:
- what we worked on was ... data harvesting programs where we would pull data from users of apps and all of their friend networks and run that data through algorithms that could profile their personality traits and other psychological attributes, wylie told cnnâ€™s don lemon monday evening.

wylie said the ultimate goal was to obtain information in order to exploit mental vulnerabilities that our algorithms showed that [facebook users] had.

in addition to wylie and cambridge analytica, accounts of cambridge analyticaâ€™s parent company, strategic communication laboratories, and those of a university of cambridge psychologist aleksandr kogan were also suspended.

the accounts were suspended because facebook received reports that data that had been shared with cambridge and wylie from koganâ€™s app may not have been completely deleted. koganâ€™s app was removed in 2015 and facebook said they had been previously provided certifications that the data had been deleted. - several days ago, we received reports that, contrary to the certifications we were given, not all data was deleted, facebook said friday. - we are moving aggressively to determine the accuracy of these claims. if true, this is another unacceptable violation of trust and the commitments they made. we are suspending scl/cambridge analytica, wylie and kogan from facebook, pending further information.

special counsel robert mueller asked cambridge analytica last fall to surrender emails from any of its employees who worked for the trump campaign, the wall street journal reported in december. the firm complied to the request.

diana stancy correll
washington examiner

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

do you feel stuck or unable to be successful in pretty much anything you try? weight, salary, your relationship, even your daily to do list let alone your 5 year goals?!? do you often ask, â€˜what am i doing wrong? why canâ€™t i have this for myself?â€™ do you ever feel completely deflated and frustrated with your lack of living? youâ€™ve put the schooling in, you have checked all the boxes, now youâ€™re waiting. when the fuck does life start? am i right? .
i used to be right there with you. and the guilt for not being able to appreciate the blessings i do have was overwhelming. i often wondered what is wrong with me. is it just me who feels this way? .
coaching woke me up. i put the work into my mindset and began to develop gratitude for everything i had. i started to see the joy in the small things. i started reshaping the problems in my life to be opportunity based and not outcome based. i started living. coaching isnâ€™t just about fitness for me. itâ€™s about learning how to be happy after 30yrs of reaching. itâ€™s about connecting to a greater purpose. itâ€™s about helping yourself so you can serve others. when you reshape your mind everything else lines up. the universe works in amazing ways and if you havenâ€™t yet started to open your eyes to that, you need to. join me in this amazing journey of abundance. .
.

text:
#bgb - a north texas teenager who falsely claimed she was kidnapped and raped by three black men last march will likely serve no prison time.

on thursday, 19-year-old breana harmon of pottsboro pleaded guilty to four felony charges of tampering with physical evidence and government documents in relation to false reports of kidnapping and sexual assault. â€œsheâ€™s very remorseful for what she did and what she said, and thatâ€™s why she decided to plead guilty,â€ harmonâ€™s attorney bob jarvis told the sherman herald democrat. no suspects were ever identified or arrested in the case.

harmon will be sentenced march 20. her plea deal has two possible punishments: regular probation or deferred adjudication, which often involves fulfilling a requirement, such as treatment or community service. neither involves prison time.  #firstthem #themfirst #metoo #freebillcosby #jussiesmollett

text:
words play a powerful role in oppression. the #metoo movement by #taranaburke clarified a lot for me. i had internalized over 40 years-worth of demeaning words. 
these seemingly innocuous words had been a factor in lowering my self-esteemâ€¦ in stifling my voice when i had something important to sayâ€¦ in keeping me from questioning the power structures in placeâ€¦ in keeping meâ€¦quiet.

if these words have had such a stronghold over my life â€“ a privileged cis-gender white woman â€“ what effect have they had over more marginalized individuals? i will never fully understand the extent, but itâ€™s my mission to empathize and act. and it makes me extremely angry.

so go ahead, call me an angry woman. i am angry. finally. and if youâ€™re not already, you should be too. -------
photos by @maria.font.photography

text:
each of these women you can see in the picture carry a story not everybody has the strength to listen to. 
after covering on foot 10,000 kilometers, spread over 24 states in 200 districts of india, this entourage of over five thousand rape survivors concluded the garima yatra/dignity march today. sharing their stories of assault along the way, they raised their voices loud enough to reach every nook and corner. amongst them were women who were raped in front of their children, women who were abducted, abused and left to bleed, women who were branded as witches by fellow villagers when they reported their assault, women who were beaten up by their families for getting abused, women who were left by their husbands, women who were raped because they belong to a lower caste, women who were raped because they tried to stop another women/girl child from being abused, women who now are mothers to their rapist's child, women who are now jobless, aimless and awfully hurt, men who lost their daughters and sisters to a sexual assault. 
each of these stories is worth an instagram post, worth a hashtag, worth a blog, yet each of these stories is so horrifying that you can barely have courage to listen to them. 
while urban women or women with access to social media reported their abuses with the #metoo  movement, these uneducated and underprivileged women sought to traditional means in order to be heard. while they might have concluded their journey, it is on us, the citizens to not let their voices fade away. 
this post is a simple reminder that an abuse is an abuse even if it didn't happen in front of your eyes, a survivor is a survivor even if she/he is not related to you, a person who reports her/his assault deserves to be heard and to be supported no matter whether she/he does so via a social media account or via a rural self help group.

#womensmarch #womenempowerment #womenunite #storiesofabuse #survivornotavictim #womenpower #sexualabuse #womensupportwomen #dignitymarch #garimayatra #metooindia #sexualharassment #sexualassault #lifeasweknowit #deathasweknowit #igdaily @shespeaksforthechange
@indianwomenblog @womensmarch @miss_matured @women.slogans

text:
a north texas teenager who falsely claimed she was kidnapped and raped by three black men last march will likely serve no prison time.

on thursday, 19-year-old breana harmon of pottsboro pleaded guilty to four felony charges of tampering with physical evidence and government documents in relation to false reports of kidnapping and sexual assault. â€œsheâ€™s very remorseful for what she did and what she said, and thatâ€™s why she decided to plead guilty,â€ harmonâ€™s attorney bob jarvis told the sherman herald democrat. no suspects were ever identified or arrested in the case.

harmon will be sentenced march 20. her plea deal has two possible punishments: regular probation or deferred adjudication, which often involves fulfilling a requirement, such as treatment or community service. neither involves prison time.  #firstthem #themfirst #metoo #freebillcosby #jussiesmollett

text:
with what iâ€™m about to say, i donâ€™t exactly know how to put my feelings into words. i am speaking out for the first time about an assult that was perputrated against me on february 6, 2019. 
it was a fucking nightmare. i was violated, verbally abused and drugged.
this was not done by just any stranger or sketchy hook up, this was a friend that iâ€™ve known for 5 years. this came out of nowhere & he held me against my will.
i thought he cared about me as a friend and person. 
i tried to reach my friends that night, i got one. he then lied to that friend of mine saying i was okay and things were fine. i was not at ease, i was not fine. 
at some point in the night he hid his charger so i wouldnâ€™t be able to charge my phone so i could leave. my phone ended up dying. he took my clothes off and shaved my entire body, including my private parts. he then called me names like retarded, handicapped, stupid, white trash and faggot. i felt all i can do is just take it and wait until itâ€™s over.
i feel like iâ€™ve been stripped down on every level. i am trying to find myself again, i donâ€™t think iâ€™ll be able to date anytime soon after this trauma i endured. i keep crying off and on. i feel ugly right now; physically and mentally.  i do not wish him harm, i hope he gets the help that he needs and i hope his soul can change for the best. 
i donâ€™t want to feel uncomfortable nor unsafe going to friends houses, club and bars; especially in the lgbt community.
i should only feel safe and welcomed. 
i have reported this crime to police, and i am getting the help i need. i know speaking out will not take the pain away but i want people to understand this can happen to anybody. you are not alone. you are strong. 
please remember to stay safe. 
#metoo
#mentoo

text:
throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaignâ€™s use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of peopleâ€™s profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there â€œcould have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheatingâ€. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesdayâ€™s hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon
the guardian

text:
i have so many mixed opinions about the controversy and critique that has followed #karllagerfeldâ€™s death. is it right to laud a man who was a bigot, racist, cringeworthy in the way he spoke against #metoo and plus-size women ... ... but was also a genius, creating experiences with fashion shows, balancing his ethos between three heavyweight brands (chanel, fendi, karl), power player. there were rocket launches in his shows, faux beaches, icebergs, enchanted forests, casinos, airports, shopping centres, protest marches, doll houses, underwater worlds... you canâ€™t deny the callousness of his comments but you also canâ€™t deny his genius. and even if, like me, youâ€™ve merely been a karl aficionado via the far reaches of the internet, you canâ€™t deny that his death is a severe loss to fashion. 
but yes, it is also a â€˜gainâ€™ for the world at large. in a world that is more aware, power players like karl canâ€™t be allowed to air out their bigotry with such pride. they set a precedent that could alarmingly be followed by so many others. 
for better and for worse, there can be no one like lagerfeld. 
#rememberingkarllagerfeld #thegoodthebadtheuglytheveryugly (images via @gettyimages)

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since day one.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop, has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are useless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is no way that gop isn't aware of this - after all, cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got as cambridge analytica. pedofiles - i bet - but the way things are bundled sure makes goebbels shiver.

trump plays along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still - the republicans willingly piggybacked this before the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaignâ€™s use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of peopleâ€™s profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there â€œcould have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheatingâ€. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesdayâ€™s hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon
the guardian

text:
construction work is dangerous - posing a danger to workers and bystanders.  when construction companies cut corners, people get hurt, and there are many ways to get compensation for the victims.  it is important to compensate victims for their pain and suffering, lost present and future lost earnings and damage to their lifestyle, but it is also important to keep construction companies in accountant for their negligent, reckless or intentional acts that cause people harm.  wittenstein & wittenstein has been helping people injured in construction accidents for over 60 years, getting the highest verdicts and settlements possible for these complicated cases.

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
my first collab with my fav @hijab._.writes â¤.. audio by;@musawiramotivates
caption by @hijab._.writes "mitti hoja mitti"â¤
insan mitti sey banaya gya hai or mitti ajzi or inkisari ki nishani hai is lehaz se insan mein bhi ajzi honi chahiye magar haqeeqat is sey mukhtilf hai insaan mein na to ajzi hai na inkisari hai khas tor p un logo mein to bilkul nhi jo ajkl apney saath high status ka tag ley ker ghomtey aik barey auhdey p pohnch k khud ko khuda smjhney lag jatey or asal khuda ka khouf unkey dilo sey mitt jatta hai wo smjhtey k wo kuch bhi krey unka koi kuch bigar ni skta ku k yaha ka qanoon or adaltein to unkey isharo p nachtey hai...unkey liye insan zindigi ki ya uskey khoon ki koi qeemat nhi hai aik amer bap ka beta kesi gareeb ko apni gari k neechae dey ker chlla jatta hai to koi shour ni uthta ku mein pochti hon kyon ni uth ta kya wo insan ni tha jisko aik ameer bap ki biggri aulad ney rat k andhere mein nashae mein dhut gari chlatey hue apni gari key neechae de diya...afsos dr afsos k insaniyat ab hamarey ander baqi na rahi ab to salam hi usey kiya jatta jiskey pass koi auhda hotta...hyeee aik mitti se bnae insaan ko apni taqat pr kitna ghamend hotta ye jantey hue bhi k uski auqat sirf itni si hai k wo mitti se bnaya gya or mitti mein hi dafna diya jaye ga or chand din matam key bad bhula bhi diya jaye ga to phir mein pochti hon kis bat ka garoor hai jab mitti se ban k mitti mein hi jaana hai or jatey hue wohi libas pahen na jo aik gareeb k jism pr hoga to kya frq tum mei or us mei uski bhi 2 gaz ki qbr or safeed kafan or tumhara bhi...anjam dono ka hi aik hai or khuda k nazdeek dono hi barber hai...aj ka almiya sirf ye hai key insaan apni auqat bhool chuka wo bhool chuka wo jis khuda k samney aker ra us khuda ki mrzi k baagair wo aik qadam chal ni skta.

text:
a poem (and sort of declaration i wrote). link to website in bio
âœ¨âœ¨
so hard on you at times,
unforgiving when you slow down,
high expectations,
low praise
you are soft like you were designed to be,
forever changing, because so am i.
spectacular, resilient, beautiful, givingâ€¦
you hold energy, life and growth 
every muscle, every roll, every stretch mark
represents me.
all i can say now, is; 
i promise to continue to nourish you
i promise to care for you
work with you
and above all, 
love you in all your different shapes and forms âœ¨âœ¨
poem by cheyenne donnelly

today in history: episode 7 -
on this day, in 17 b.c.(before crenshaw), jacob latimer of nethapolin discovered what would become the building blocks of modern society. it started out like any other day, kids roaming the poop pits, camels milking the neighbors, and women kneeling in formation when men approached. as the day went on however, jacob began to notice something was off. when he was using the women as steps to his bathhouse, he noticed one was missing. this was extremely unusual because it was his wife, step #6, that was the one missing. he summoned his servant, dillinger domingo, who was just a wee lad of about 7. dillinger searched far and near for her. when he finally found her, he could not believe what he saw. he reported it immediately to jacob, who was equally appalled at the heinous scene. she had been laying with the pigs in the mud pits. he shouted, â€œyouâ€™re silly, youâ€™re lazy, and youâ€™re gerfin!!!!!â€ thus the term slag(silly lazy and gerfin), was born, and to this day it has been upheld that all women are in fact, slags.
-

text:
"for as long as i can remember, i've been haunted by the feeling that "it's never good enough." #metoo ğŸ˜µ i can relate to that sentence! i believe that is why #brenebrown books are so relatable to me! i am enough. it doesn't matter what your religion is, what your ethnic background, or what your sexual preference is, we all struggle with the feeling that "it's never good enough."
.
ğŸ¦‹
i was constantly trying to fill that void inside me. there was never enough alcohol or pain killers to fix me. they were slowly destroying my soul. i could read all self-help books, post all the inspirational quotes, try to fake my happiness, anything but get honest with myself. i didn't feel worthy of god's love, my husband's love, my kids love, the list is endless. i didn't love myself.
.
ğŸ¦‹
it wasn't until i was willing to get really uncomfortable that i realized that i was always good enough. god loves unconditionally. i was already enough. getting honest with myself, was an extremely difficult process but i can do the hard things sober. walking through my hurt was the bravest and most honorable thing i've done in my 35 years. being truly authentic and vulnerable is where the magic happens. happy friday! you are already enough!

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby," said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said.
.
- the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
hey everyone! happy friday. i hope that you have had an amazing week. after a lot of consideration, i have finally launched my podcast. it would mean a lot if you take a listen. welcome to the first episode of the think unbroken podcast hosted by michael anthony. in this episode i talk about growing up in trauma in the midwest, falling into the vortex, the moment everything changed, and why i decided to start a podcast. this is the first of many podcasts in which i will break down my own experiences and how i transformed my life. the goal of this podcast is to give other trauma warriors the tools to find health, sustainability, and happiness.

links in the bio.

https://soundcloud.com/thinkunbroken/think-unbroken-podcast-episode-1

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are useless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is no way that gop isn't aware of this - after all, cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got as cambridge analytica. pedofiles - i bet - but the way things are bundled sure makes goebbels shiver.

trump plays along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still - the republicans willingly piggybacked this before the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

name: Seth Rich Nietzsche

ãƒ»ãƒ»ãƒ»
fixed it!  so from a legal and human rights perspective, my version is more accurate.  how on earth, then, do we have it so reversed??
.
for one, patients, providers, and the public are unaware of the rights of birthing people.  yes, all three of those groups.  most people believe that the doctor "ultimately" has the right to make decisions about birth.
.
obviously, this contributes to a lot of problems: skyrocketing induction and c-section rates, birth trauma and ptsd, and yeah, i'll say it--even more reinforcement of truly messed up cultural beliefs and norms around how women and mothers are valued.  which is to say, not very much.  the birth room is where prejudice, sexism, racism, classism, and all kinds of other -isms converge on individuals at their absolute most vulnerable.
.
how do we flip that on its head?  we start with education.  i'll tell you what, it pissed me off when i found out after the fact that i had always had the right to say "no" to an induction being pushed on me.  i always thought i would have advocated for myself that much more confidently if i had known just how strong my rights were and what they were based on.
.
doulas and birth workers: you are the front line for this kind of education.  if you took my class, you'd understand why i feel so confident saying: "hospital policies are really preferences.  birth plans are really policies." (p.s. i tag acog in most of these posts, just in case anyoneâ€™s listening.)
.
tonight is the last night to get this class at a great intro price--over 25% off.  you have until midnight.  so get on it!  bit.ly/birth-rights
.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytica $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
when we think about chanel, we think about something we want, idealized or some, hopefully, we directly buy it. chanel is aspiration. 
since we were young or since when we read magazines, chanel has been something linked to chic and elegant women. those are clothes and accessories that elevate your look at the moment. having a garment from â€˜the maisonâ€™ makes you feel closer to those people whom we consider stylish. chanel definitely is status, it is not available to everyone, neither economically nor in others. by this we mean that few people can understand or appreciate the artisan work behind a garment, the idea of which part of the collection or why chanel reinterprets the piece . also, chanel is personality. after all behind each collection is the brand of a woman who was a pioneer in everything. she was a feminist before the #metoo and did not mind working and alternate with millionaires, artists or dukes but always vindicating her independence, in all aspects. chanel is a lot ofthings. so when you wear chanel, it's not just a garment. 
with karl, an era ends but another begins ... it has been the destiny that has made it re-directed by a woman?

coco could not be more happier. right hand of lagerfeld , @virginieviardoffical dominates like no one the aesthetic codes of the maison. if karl has designated her as an heiress, we do not doubt that she represents the spirit of the house better than anyone! we are expectant to see with what surprises us and to know about what we will dream. 
in the end, is not just trying to aspire to have. it is about trying to be (a chanel woman). #chanel #virginieviard #karllagerfeld #paris #french #ootd #cocochanel

text:
throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaignâ€™s use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of peopleâ€™s profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there â€œcould have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheatingâ€. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesdayâ€™s hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon
the guardian

text: september 2015 i surprised you all by posting hours before my emergency #brain #surgery that i might die but that i knew i'd be speaking to all again soon. it took some time but i kept my word. in 2016, i told you all i'm still adjusting to my new #invisibledisabilities but i'm going to push thru and start my #weightloss process that summer, even against my pcp advice. in 2017, i brought in the year 75 pounds down and counting, by spring i was certified in my first #zumba instructor course (#zumbagold) the same course that i started 10 months after becoming a #brainsurgerysurvivor. in 2017 i launched my umbrella company #visionaryv and told you all i would be expanding. january 2018, i signed my #dumbo lease for my #holistic #wellness suite and opened to the public on 2/15. was able to work on and get two new laws signed both taking effect this year, 2019. in addition, i collaborated with another organization and #visionaryvministries went on our first international #missions trip to #kingston #jamaica. now february 2019, i'm launching #visionaryvuniversity. still have my daily struggles, still sit connected to infusion machines one day every week but i'm here and thriving. i could be home on full disability and no one would question me but i wasn't ready to give up on my dreams and goals. i wasn't done serving my purpose. i wasn't ready to throw the towel in. i made a promise to myself one day after my #brain #surgery home alone on the floor crawling to the bathroom because my legs were too weak, that i wasn't going to let myself, nor my son down!!! might not be rich yet, however my word is my bond and that my dear is, priceless. someone is at their wits end but today i'm here to tell you to look past your pain and pull from your inner strength. - ms. v #yupstillblessedandverygrateful #ididnotsurvivebrainsurgerytoliveamediocrelife #thepowerofyou #blesseditbe #lifecoach #wellnesscoach #survivor #metoo #rapesurvivor #fostercare #singlemom #disabledparent #motivationalspeaker #keynotespeaker
name: Dr. V, Founder of Visionary V

text:
if you feel pain where the tendon (medial epicondyle) attaches to the inside of the elbow â€“ that bumpy part that tingles when we knock it. chances are you are experiencing golfer elbow ğŸŒï¸â€â™‚ï¸ .
the main symptoms of golfers elbow are pain and tenderness around the bony bit on the inside of the elbow called the medial epicondyle, particularly when gripping hard with the hand. it is also not unusual to experience a general weakness in our wrists, with pain occurring when bending our wrist palm downwards against any resistance.
.
initially, the pain and inflammation can be relieved though the use of non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs such as ibuprofen or aspirin while applying the p.o.l.i.c.e principle;

protection â€“ protect the forearm / elbow / wrist from being aggravated further.
.
optimal loading â€“ this means that rather than resting the elbow and waiting, recovery can be sped up by using the muscles affected at a restricted level to help stimulate the cells in the recovery process. this always prevents the muscles from weakening and shortening.
.
ice â€“ use ice immediately after the injury occurs to prevent inflammation.
compression â€“ the use of a support or taping will help compress the affected area, immobilising and protecting it also.
.
elevation â€“ elevate the hand /arm immediately to reduce pain and blood flow to the injured area.
should your injury worsen over time or continue to cause you issues, 
physiotherapy is encouraged.
.
do tag your friends who might be experiencing the same too

text:
dit mooie boek haalde ik deze week weer uit de kast om verder te lezen. ik begon erin bij het ecodorp aardehuis vlak voor nieuwjaar 2018. afgelopen jaar heb ik het boek er geregeld bij gepakt. ğŸ‘‰ğŸ»maya angelou: "iedereen die kan lezen, zou dit boek moeten lezen."
ğŸŒ hoe meer ik me in de materie verdiep, hoe meer ik me realiseer dat er nog vele 'ongetemde' schatten aan wijsheid te ontdekken zijn... dit boek heeft vele vrouwen geraakt. en via hen ook mannen, in het dagelijkse leven, dat weet ik zeker. het boek zelf is niet zo transformerend maar wanneer je daadwerkelijk bepaalde routines en rituelen in je leven integreert, wordt het different. 
er zijn (ook in nederland) diverse succesvolle ondermemersgroepen actief die vanuit een sisterhood openheid een sociale shift creeren. ik heb kosteloos aan enkele masterclasses met geleide meditaties deelgenomen. eye openers! 
de relatie tussen mind, body en earth/space staat centraal. het is een wonderlijke tijd, wow. ook relevant t.a.v.  diversiteitsbeleid, mixed genders en economie, want empathie speelt in deze beweging een krachtige en geen ondergesneeuwde rol. en doordat vrouwen helder vanuit hun hart handelen hebben mannen een duidelijker beeld van hun wensen en mogelijkheden. ğŸ’›ğŸ’¥ samen maken we een einde aan machtsmisbruik en daar bloeit de samenleving van! #metoo not anymore! er is een beweging ondernemers opgestaan die (ook met mannen) van binnen uit een verschil wil maken. 
vier de rijkdom van de natuur, connect met je essentie en neem van daaruit actie. dat is duurzaam ondernemerschap, geleid door je hart en wederzijdse understanding. met omzet en impact; laat beperkende overtuigingen los. en zet je 'oerangsten' via acceptatie, om in daadkracht. je angsten recht aan durven kijken, dat is de crux

text:
recently a lot has changed very quickly. 
i found out someone i once deeply feared now keenly monitors everything i post online, when it used to be the other way around. 
after the shock of knowing i have my first fan as a budding writer passed, i realised that while itâ€™s an unnerving role reversal, it also shows me i have actually come a long way. 
proving this, today i signed a contract for a dream job!
before everythingâ„¢ happened work was equal parts vocation and obligation. but now that iâ€™ve experienced what being out of action feels like, even the most basic campaign task is the most exciting thing in the world. 
i start in just over a week. 
i cannot wait.
#surviving #trauma #ptsd #rapevictim #rapesurvivor #metoo #ibelieveher #womenswave

text:
our post is still blowing up, so we've posted this image as the most common arguments by rape apologists on the thread are that she, greta, "doesn't appear to be resisting", isn't flailing or trying to push the man off, and that she looks fine. all common arguments used to dismiss sexual assault survivors today, many of whom have been in greta's position or similar positions. people say we shouldn't bother talking about anything serious concerning this image because greta brushed it off later in life, as if that magically erases what takes place in this and three other photos of the same event. 
this begs the question, why do people so badly want people to be okay with what took place in this photo. they so badly want people to not view it as sexual assault, even though it so clearly is an image of sexual assault.do they have a guilty conscience, maybe? it's no shocker that many of these people are cishet men and white women in their early 30's to 60's. they like to take the easy route and cite the time period or blame the #metoo movement. not a day goes by where some incel or trumpette finds a reason to attack the #metoo movement. there's something more going on with these people who are so eager to keep the romantic ideal of this problematic image. 
just because sexual assault was normalized in the 40's and not discussed in depth like it is today, does not mean we should sweep history under the rug. it is not okay, and there is no excuse, to grab a person and force yourself on them. it doesn't matter if you wear a uniform or plain clothes, if you know them or just looked at them once. no one is entitled to another person's body.

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
sosok kevin halim menarik perhatian kami saat ia menjadi salah satu pembicara di acara seminar kekerasan seksual di dunia kerja yang diadakan oleh perempuan mahardhika dalam rangaikan 16 hari anti kekerasan terhadap perempuan tahun 2018 lalu. tim never okay project kemudian berkesempatan untuk berbincang dengan kevin halim, seorang transpuan berusia 27 tahun yang saat ini bekerja sebagai trans deputy program untuk gaya warna lentera indonesia atau yang biasa disebut gwl ina.

pada pertemuan ini, kevin menceritakan seputar pekerjaannya dan perhatiannya terhadap komunitas transgender yang harus menghadapi tantangan tersendiri di dunia kerja. kevin juga membagikan pendapatnya kepada kami mengenai pelecehan seksual di tempat kerja.

#sayneverokay #neverokayproject #metoo #gerakbersama
name: Never Okay
tweet_full:

pada pertemuan ini, kevin menceritakan seputar pekerjaannya dan perhatiannya terhadap komunitas transgender yang harus menghadapi tantangan tersendiri di dunia kerja. kevin juga membagikan pendapatnya kepada kami mengenai pelecehan seksual di tempat kerja.

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters
